<P>
<U><B>Abstract:</B></U>

<P>
Cellular networks show different functionality. 
In  <i>E.coli</i> the  phosphoenolpyruvate: 
carbohydrate phosphotransferase system acts like a sensory element which is
able to measure the flux through glycolysis. Since the output of the sensor is
connected to the activity of the global transcription factor Crp, the  kinetic
and structural properties of the system are important for the understanding of
the overall cellular behavior. <br><br>

 A family of mathematical models is presented that show a
structurally and quantitatively robust behavior.
A central element that is responsible for the structural
robustness is a feed-forward loop, a well known motif in <i>E. coli</i>.
 The models describe a set of experimental data that relates the output of the
 sensor to the specific grwoth rate.
 <br><br>

MATLAB files for model simulations are available on 
http://www.mpi-magdeburg.mpg.de/people/kre/robust/ <br> 
A short description of the files provided on this site can be found in the
Supporting information. 

<br>
<br>

<U><B>Downloads:</B></U>

<P>
 <a href="files_dot_m.zip"> Download MATLAB 
"*.m" file  </a>
that allow simulation of the system and comparison with experimental data.
<br>
<br>
 <a href="files_dot_mat.zip"> Download "files_dot_mat.zip"  </a>
zipped file with experimental data and the optimal parameters. 
<br>
<br>
To start the simulation, download the .zip files, unzip, and store in
the same directory. Start programs as described in the Appendix
<br><br>
Example: evalu('opti_m1',1)
<br
<br>
gives back the sigma value and plots the results.
